In [14]:
def Categorical_pie_charts(data,m):
    a = []
    for i in data:
        a.append(i)
    
    b = []
    for i in a:
        if (data[i].dtype.name) == 'object':
            b.append(i)
        
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 25))
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)
    plt.suptitle("Pie-Charts for Categorical Variables in the dataframe", fontsize=18, y=0.95)
    
    ncols = m
    nrows = len(b) // ncols + (len(b) % ncols > 0)

    for n, i in enumerate(b):
        ax = plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, n + 1)

        data.groupby(i).size().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.2f%%',ax=ax)
        
        ax.set_title(i.upper())
        ax.set_xlabel("")
        ax.set_ylabel("")
    plt.show()

Share insights for Q2.c

-->Churn: 26.6 % of customers switched to another firm based on churn pie chart.

-->Gender Ratio: Customers are 49.5 % female and 50.5 % male.

-->Contract: High number of contracts of month to month basis than higher tenures of 1-2 years

-->Payment method: Electronic check and mailed cheque have high percentage as compared to automatic payment methods. People with automatic payment methods are less likely to move out.

-->Paperless billing: High percentage of customers opted for paperless billing.

-->Percentage of no internet service in columns like Online security, online backup,device protection, techsupport, streaming TV and streaming movies is exactly same and percentage of users who have not opted for these services is high as compared to users who have opted.

--> More numbers of users are without parters or dependents

-->Most of the users have opted for fiberoptic internet service as compared to others like DSL

In [18]:
#Defining the map function
def bin_map(feature):
    return feature.map({'Yes':1, 'No':0})

## Encoding target feature
data['Churn'] = data[['Churn']].apply(bin_map)

# Encoding gender category
data['gender'] = data['gender'].map({'Male':1, 'Female':0})

#Encoding other binary category
bin_list = ['Partner', 'Dependents', 'PhoneService', 'PaperlessBilling']
data[bin_list] = data[bin_list].apply(bin_map)

#Encoding the other categoric features with more than two categories
data = pd.get_dummies(data, drop_first=True)

Pie charts to for categorical features to see the percentage distribution of features

In [8]:
def Categorical_pie_charts1(data,m):
    a = []
    for i in data:
        a.append(i)
    
    b = []
    for i in a:
        if (data[i].dtype.name) == 'object':
            b.append(i)
        
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 25))
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)
    plt.suptitle("Pie-Charts for Categorical Variables in the dataframe", fontsize=18, y=0.95)
    
    ncols = m
    nrows = len(b) // ncols + (len(b) % ncols > 0)

    for n, i in enumerate(b):
        ax = plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, n + 1)

        data.groupby(i).size().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.2f%%',ax=ax)
        
        ax.set_title(i.upper())
        ax.set_xlabel("")
        ax.set_ylabel("")
    plt.show()

#Defining the map function
def bin_map(feature):
    return feature.map({'Yes':1, 'No':0})

## Encoding target feature
finaldf['Churn'] = finaldf[['Churn']].apply(bin_map)

# Encoding gender category
finaldf['gender'] = finaldf['gender'].map({'Male':1, 'Female':0})

#Encoding other binary category
bin_list = ['Partner', 'Dependents', 'PhoneService', 'PaperlessBilling']
finaldf[bin_list] = finaldf[bin_list].apply(bin_map)

#Encoding the other categoric features with more than two categories
finaldf = pd.get_dummies(finaldf, drop_first=True)

In [46]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

def preprocessing_(finaldf, option):
   
    #Defining the map function
    def bin_map(feature):
        return feature.map({'Yes':1, 'No':0})
        finaldf['Churn'] = finaldf[['Churn']].apply(bin_map)

        finaldf['gender'] = finaldf['gender'].map({'Male':1, 'Female':0})

        bin_list = ['Partner', 'Dependents', 'PhoneService', 'PaperlessBilling']
        finaldf[bin_list] = finaldf[bin_list].apply(bin_map)


        finaldf = pd.get_dummies(finaldf, drop_first=True)

    #feature scaling
    sc = MinMaxScaler()
    finaldf['tenure'] = sc.fit_transform(finaldf[['tenure']])
    finaldf['MonthlyCharges'] = sc.fit_transform(finaldf[['MonthlyCharges']])
    finaldf['TotalCharges'] = sc.fit_transform(finaldf[['TotalCharges']])
    
    return finaldf

Function to predict various model scores

In [20]:
def modeling(alg, alg_name, params={}):
    model = alg(**params)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    #Performance evaluation
    def print_scores(alg, y_true, y_pred):
        print(alg_name)
        acc_score = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
        print("accuracy: ",acc_score)
        pre_score = precision_score(y_true, y_pred)
        print("precision: ",pre_score)
        rec_score = recall_score(y_true, y_pred)                            
        print("recall: ",rec_score)
        f_score = f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average='weighted')
        print("f1_score: ",f_score)

    print_scores(alg, y_test, y_pred)
    return model

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
##Defining paramters and grid
grid1={'solver': ('liblinear', 'newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'sag', 'saga'),"penalty":["l1","l2"],"C":[-1,0,1,10,100]}

logres=LogisticRegression() #model
logres_cv=GridSearchCV(logres,grid1,cv=10)
logres_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)

#summarizing results

print("Best parameters :",logres_cv.best_params_)
print("accuracy :",logres_cv.score(X_test,y_test))
